Lets make word clouds of the five-star reviews

tokens %>%
  filter(stars == 5) %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  filter(n > 50) %>% 
  with(wordcloud(word, n, max.words = 100))

and one of the one-star reviews:

tokens %>%
  filter(stars == 1) %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  filter(n > 50) %>% 
  with(wordcloud(word, n, max.words = 100))

Lets compute average star ratings per words:

avg_star <- tokens %>% group_by(word) %>% 
  summarize(stars = mean(stars))

Some of these averages are suspicious because they are exactly 1, 3, 4 or 5 which suggests that they are based on perhaps one review. Lets count how frequently each word occurs and merge this to

avg_star <- tokens %>% count(word) %>%
  right_join(avg_star) %>% arrange(desc(n))
## Joining, by = "word"

Lets take only words that occurred at least 10 times (this is a pretty arbitrary threshold, you may want to think of a better one):

avg_star <- avg_star %>% filter(n >= 10)
nrow(avg_star)
## [1] 5085

We are left with ~5000 some words.

Lets look at those words that occur in reviews with really high or low average review stars:

Lets see whether these star ratings correlate with emotional valence ratings that were collected in isolation (norms), using the data from Warriner et al. (2013):

war <- read_csv('warriner_2013_cleaned.csv')
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Word = col_character(),
##   Val = col_double(),
##   Val_z = col_double()
## )
avg_star <- left_join(avg_star, war, by = c('word' = 'Word'))

Make a plot of this relationship:

avg_star %>% ggplot(aes(x = Val, y = stars)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 2464 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

How strong is this correlation?

with(avg_star, cor(Val, stars, use = 'complete.obs'))
## [1] 0.4037077

r = 0.4 Id say thats pretty decent!

Average N pos/neg words per review:

For this, lets use a standard sentiment lexicon, the Bing et al. one this is pretty coarse. Its relatively small and has a categorical scheme (positive / negative). While that may not correspond to your theory of emotional valence (which may be continuous), dealing with words that are treated as EITHER positive OR negative is sometimes useful for presentatinal purporses.

The bing lexicon comes with the sentimentr package that is part of tidytext, and it can be retrieved via the get_sentiments() function:

bing <- get_sentiments('bing')

Join this with the tokens data frame:

bingtokens <- inner_join(tokens, bing)
## Joining, by = "word"
bingtokens
## # A tibble: 64,277 x 4
##    review_id              stars word      sentiment
##    <chr>                  <int> <chr>     <chr>    
##  1 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 break     negative 
##  2 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 fun       positive 
##  3 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 friendly  positive 
##  4 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 fun       positive 
##  5 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 honest    positive 
##  6 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 enjoyed   positive 
##  7 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 hilarious positive 
##  8 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 enjoyed   positive 
##  9 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 recommend positive 
## 10 GQFbfIkSyDcXA_vCcyQoxQ     5 bonus     positive 
## # ... with 64,267 more rows

Lets compute the number of positive and negative words per review:

pos_per_review <- bingtokens %>%
  count(review_id, index = sentiment) %>%
  spread(index, n, fill = 0)

Lets calculate the total number of evaluative words and exclude those for which we have less than 5 words (not much to say there). Lets also compute the proportion of positive words for each review:

pos_per_review <- pos_per_review %>%
  mutate(sum = negative + positive,
         prop = positive / sum) %>% 
  filter(sum >= 5)

Lets get the stars from the main table in there:

pos_per_review <- yelp %>%
  select(-text) %>%
  right_join(pos_per_review)
## Joining, by = "review_id"

Lets see how well the proportion of positive to negative words predicts the restaurant review ratings:

mymdl <- lm(stars ~ prop, data = pos_per_review)
glance(mymdl)
##   r.squared adj.r.squared   sigma statistic p.value df    logLik      AIC
## 1 0.4418118     0.4417087 1.06555  4286.029       0  2 -8029.321 16064.64
##        BIC deviance df.residual
## 1 16084.43 6148.174        5415

An r-squared of 0.44 thats pretty high!

Whats the correlation coefficient then?

with(pos_per_review, cor(stars, prop))
## [1] 0.6646892

r = 0.66 thats pretty high!

Using the sentimentr package

Get reviews at the sentence level and perform the sentiment function from the sentimentr package on it. This takes amplifiers and negators into account (see description of algorithm in the sentimentr readme).

Lets check that this works:

sentiment(c('This is good', 'This is not good', 'This is very good', 'This is really good','This is excellent'))
##    element_id sentence_id word_count  sentiment
## 1:          1           1          3  0.4330127
## 2:          2           1          4 -0.3750000
## 3:          3           1          4  0.6750000
## 4:          4           1          4  0.6750000
## 5:          5           1          3  0.5773503

Not good correctly receives a negative sentiment, andvery good" and really good are treated as better than good. Also, excellent is better than good, which intuitively makes sense.

sentences <- get_sentences(yelp$text)
mysent <- sentiment(sentences)
mysent
##        element_id sentence_id word_count  sentiment
##     1:          1           1         18 0.00000000
##     2:          1           2         10 0.07905694
##     3:          1           3         13 0.00000000
##     4:          1           4          4 0.40000000
##     5:          1           5         12 0.14433757
##    ---                                             
## 84035:      10000           1         14 0.40089186
## 84036:      10000           2         21 0.22912878
## 84037:      10000           3         16 0.46250000
## 84038:      10000           4         26 0.29417420
## 84039:      10000           5          6 0.30618622

To compare this to the Yelp reviews stars, we want to average the sentence-level sentiments by review.

myavgs <- mysent %>% group_by(element_id) %>% 
  summarize(sentiment = mean(sentiment, na.rm = TRUE))

Append this to the main tibble:

yelp <- bind_cols(yelp, myavgs)

See whether they are correlated:

yelp %>% ggplot(aes(x = sentiment, y = stars)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.5, width = 0) +
  theme_minimal()

Use sentiment to predict stars:

with(yelp, cor(sentiment, stars))
## [1] 0.6096696
mymdl <- lm(stars ~ sentiment, data = yelp)
glance(mymdl)
##   r.squared adj.r.squared    sigma statistic p.value df    logLik      AIC
## 1  0.371697     0.3716341 1.136639  5914.704       0  2 -15469.14 30944.29
##        BIC deviance df.residual
## 1 30965.92  12916.9        9998

Interestingly, we dont get too much extra leverage out of this sophisticated algorithm.
